FILL_CH9 = {
  "9": {
    "1": "<p>The sending of the Twelve invokes the Jewish <em>sheliach</em> institution: an authorized representative who acts with the full legal and social authority of the sender. The <em>shaliach</em>&#8217;s actions are as binding as if the sender performed them; refusal of the <em>shaliach</em> is refusal of the sender (v.48 makes this principle explicit). Jesus confers both <em>dynamis</em> (power, miraculous ability) and <em>exousia</em> (authority, delegated legal status) &#8212; the two components that legitimize the representative&#8217;s acts in the sender&#8217;s name.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The mission has two inseparable elements: proclamation (<em>k&#275;ryssein t&#275;n basileian tou theou</em>) and healing (<em>i&#257;sthai</em>). In Second Temple Jewish expectation, the coming of the kingdom involved both the defeat of evil powers and the healing of physical afflictions (Isa 35:5-6; 4Q521); the two tasks are not distinct but constitute a single reality. The disciples&#8217; practice extends what Jesus has been doing personally throughout chs. 4&#8211;8 &#8212; the mission is meant to multiply his presence throughout Galilee before the Jerusalem journey.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The instruction to take nothing for the journey (no staff, bag, bread, money, extra tunic) is a deliberate reliance on Jewish hospitality obligations. The Didache (ca. 100 CE, chs. 11&#8211;13) preserves rules for receiving traveling prophets and teachers: a community was obligated to house and feed a legitimate teacher for a limited period. Jesus&#8217;s instruction presupposes this hospitality network; the disciples are to depend on it entirely. The prohibition on a second tunic means they cannot sleep outdoors &#8212; they must find hosts. This creates a dependence that also creates community bonds.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&#8220;Whatever house you enter, stay there until you leave that town&#8221; &#8212; the instruction to remain in one house per town prevents the social climbing that would occur if disciples moved to a more prestigious household after initial reception. In the Mediterranean patronage system, accepting hospitality from a wealthier host over a less wealthy original host was an insult to the first host. The single-house rule establishes social stability and prevents the mission from becoming entangled in village honor-competitions.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&#8220;Shake the dust off your feet as a testimony against them&#8221; (<em>eis martyrion ep autous</em>) &#8212; Jews returning from Gentile territory shook dust from their feet to avoid contaminating the Holy Land with Gentile impurity (cf. m. Ohalot 2:3). Here the gesture is applied to Jewish towns that reject the messengers &#8212; a solemn declaration that the rejecting town is being treated as outside the covenant community. The &#8220;testimony against them&#8221; functions as a legal witness that the offer was made and refused; it will be evidence at the eschatological judgment.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The successful Galilean mission (they proclaimed the good news and healed everywhere) is briefly narrated before the ominous transition to Herod&#8217;s perplexity. The itinerant village-to-village pattern (<em>kata tas k&#333;mas</em>) reflects the social geography of Galilee: a region of small agricultural villages (typically 500&#8211;2000 inhabitants) clustered around a few administrative centers. Jesus and his disciples work the village network rather than the urban centers &#8212; a deliberate strategy of reaching the rural poor before any elite response.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Herod Antipas, tetrarch of Galilee and Perea (4 BCE&#8211;39 CE), executed John the Baptist after John&#8217;s condemnation of his marriage to Herodias (3:19&#8211;20). His perplexity (<em>di&#275;porei</em>) at Jesus reflects the competing popular identifications that Luke repeats in v.18&#8211;19. Herod appears again in Luke 23:7&#8211;12 (the passion interrogation) and Acts 4:27 (Herod and Pilate allied against Jesus). Luke&#8217;s sustained attention to Herod serves both political-apologetic and fulfillment-of-prophecy themes.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The three popular identifications of Jesus (John Baptist raised, Elijah appeared, an ancient prophet risen) reflect distinct Second Temple Jewish eschatological expectations: Mal 4:5 predicted Elijah&#8217;s return before the Day of the LORD; Deut 18:15&#8211;18 promised a prophet like Moses; the Enoch-Elijah tradition (both taken without dying) supported belief in the return of earlier prophets. The early Christian debate about whether John was Elijah (Matt 11:14; 17:12&#8211;13) and whether Jesus was the prophet-like-Moses reflects these same categories.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&#8220;I had John beheaded. Who, then, is this?&#8221; &#8212; Herod&#8217;s self-incriminating acknowledgment establishes his guilt early. Josephus (<em>Ant.</em> 18.116&#8211;119) records that John was imprisoned at Machaerus (a fortress-palace east of the Dead Sea) and executed because Herod feared his popular influence might spark a revolt. Luke omits the detailed Salome-dance account (Mark 6:21&#8211;28), streamlining to focus on Herod&#8217;s ongoing desire to see Jesus &#8212; an interest that leads to the passion interrogation of 23:7&#8211;12.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The apostles&#8217; return with their mission report marks the conclusion of the first sending. The withdrawal to Bethsaida (in Philip&#8217;s tetrarchy, east of the Jordan) removes the group from Herod Antipas&#8217;s territory &#8212; significant given Herod&#8217;s just-expressed desire to see Jesus (v.9). Bethsaida was the hometown of Philip, Andrew, and Peter (John 1:44); the private withdrawal to a familiar city is also a strategic retreat from the growing public pressure in Galilee.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The crowds&#8217; pursuit despite the withdrawal reflects the pattern of messianic popular enthusiasm since ch. 4. Jesus&#8217;s response (welcome, teaching, healing) is the pattern of the messianic ministry: word and deed together. The crowds are not dismissed as an intrusion but welcomed as the primary recipients of the kingdom announcement. Luke&#8217;s triple summary (welcomed, spoke about the kingdom, healed those needing healing) will be abbreviated in the apostolic mission of Acts as &#8220;proclaiming the kingdom of God and teaching&#8221; (Acts 28:31).</p>",
    "12": "<p>The late-afternoon timing (<em>h&#275; h&#275;mera &#275;rxato kl&#299;nein</em>, the day began to decline) makes the disciples&#8217; suggestion urgent: by the time the problem is identified, it is too late for the crowd to reach surrounding villages before nightfall. The <em>er&#275;mos</em> (deserted, wilderness) setting positions the feeding as wilderness-typology: Israel in the desert, receiving food from God. The Twelve&#8217;s three-part assessment (surrounding villages, countryside, find food and lodging) reflects their logistical realism about the Galilean region&#8217;s resources.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&#8220;You give them something to eat&#8221; &#8212; the command transforms the disciples from observers to participants. Their response (five loaves and two fish) presents the real resources available. Five barley loaves and two dried fish were a standard Galilean laborer&#8217;s meal; the quantity is adequate for one person, absurdly inadequate for five thousand. The proposal to go buy food frames the miraculous alternative: the disciples&#8217; natural solution (purchase) is replaced by the divine solution (multiplication), drawing the contrast between economic and eschatological provision.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&#8220;About five thousand men&#8221; (<em>andres h&#333;sei pentakischilioi</em>) &#8212; the word <em>andres</em> (adult males) was the standard headcount unit in large gatherings; including women and children (Matt 14:21) the total would have been substantially higher. The instruction to sit in groups of fifty (<em>klinias h&#333;sei ana pent&#275;konta</em>) has been compared to the Qumran community&#8217;s organized assembly structure (1QS 2:21&#8211;23: divisions of thousands, hundreds, fifties, tens), suggesting a quasi-messianic-assembly organization of the crowd.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The disciples&#8217; compliance and the crowd&#8217;s seating is a fulfillment notice that also serves the narrative: the structured seating makes distribution possible and allows the twelve-basket count of v.17 to be verifiable. The disciples&#8217; obedience to an apparently impractical instruction (seat five thousand with inadequate food available) is itself a small act of faith &#8212; acting on the teacher&#8217;s word before the miracle is visible.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The four verbs (taking, looking up to heaven, giving thanks, breaking and giving) match the Last Supper institution pattern (22:19) and the Emmaus recognition moment (24:30). This is Luke&#8217;s deliberate Eucharistic patterning: the feeding miracle is both a messianic sign and a foretaste of the Lord&#8217;s Supper. Looking up to heaven (<em>anablepsen eis ton ouranon</em>) was the standard posture of Jewish blessing prayer; the bread-blessing formula (<em>baruch Attah Adonai&#8230;</em>) directed gratitude to the divine source of provision.</p>",
    "17": "<p>&#8220;Twelve basketfuls of broken pieces left over&#8221; &#8212; the twelve baskets are almost universally read as symbolic of the twelve tribes of Israel: the messianic feast restores and overflows provision for the whole covenant people. The abundance echoes eschatological feast promises of Isa 25:6&#8211;8 and 2 Bar. 29:5 (in the messianic era, vines will yield extraordinary abundance). The overflow-surplus signals that the messianic age exceeds all need &#8212; the exact reversal of the wilderness scarcity that Israel experienced.</p>",
    "18": "<p>&#8220;Jesus was praying in private&#8221; (Luke&#8217;s unique detail) &#8212; the great Christological question is posed in a prayer context, linking the identity disclosure to the Father-Son relationship that prayer embodies. Luke&#8217;s unique emphasis on Jesus&#8217;s prayer life (3:21; 5:16; 6:12; 9:18; 9:28&#8211;29; 11:1; 22:41&#8211;44) consistently frames major revelations and decisions. The disciples&#8217; presence &#8220;with him&#8221; while he prays alone is the paradox of intimacy and distinction that characterizes the inner group.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The three popular identifications (John Baptist, Elijah, one of the ancient prophets risen) are exactly the options Herod was unable to decide between in v.7&#8211;8. The repetition links popular messianic speculation to the formal Christological question. John the Baptist as risen makes no historical sense but reflects confusion of their missions in the popular mind. The Elijah identification carries the weight of Mal 4:5; the ancient prophet recalls Deut 18:15&#8211;18 and the Enoch-Elijah tradition of the righteous who return.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Peter&#8217;s answer &#8220;God&#8217;s Messiah&#8221; (<em>ton Christon tou theou</em>) is the high point of the Galilean ministry; it will not be publicly proclaimed again until the triumphal entry (19:38) and the trial (22:67&#8211;70). &#8220;God&#8217;s Messiah&#8221; is a distinctive formulation &#8212; not just &#8220;the Messiah&#8221; but &#8220;God&#8217;s Anointed,&#8221; echoing Ps 2:2 (&#8220;the LORD and his anointed&#8221;) and the Servant-Anointed figure of Isa 61:1. The identification is complete and accurate; its meaning will only become clear through the passion and resurrection.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The strict secrecy command (<em>parangeilas autois m&#275;deni legein touto</em>) follows immediately after the Messianic confession. The reason is not denial but context-control: the popular messianic categories of the day (Davidic warrior-king, Maccabean-style liberator) would distort the announcement; the passion prediction of v.22 provides the necessary correction. Jesus is not forbidding the truth but requiring it be understood correctly &#8212; and correct understanding requires the cross to be integral to the definition of &#8220;Messiah.&#8221;</p>",
    "22": "<p>The first passion prediction (&#8220;the Son of Man <em>must</em> suffer&#8221;, <em>dei pathein</em>) introduces the divine-necessity language that structures Luke&#8217;s passion theology. The <em>dei</em> (must, it is necessary) recurs at 13:33; 17:25; 22:37; 24:7; 24:26; 24:44 &#8212; it frames the passion as fulfillment of divine plan (<em>boul&#275; tou theou</em>), not tragic accident. The three-party rejection (elders, chief priests, scribes = the Sanhedrin&#8217;s three constituent bodies) and the third-day resurrection form the structure that 24:7 will explicitly recall.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&#8220;Take up their cross daily and follow me&#8221; &#8212; the cross was the Roman instrument of execution for non-citizens guilty of sedition; condemned prisoners carried the <em>patibulum</em> (horizontal crossbeam) through public streets to the execution site. For a Galilean audience under Roman occupation the image was viscerally concrete. The word &#8220;daily&#8221; (<em>kath&#8217; h&#275;meran</em>, unique to Luke) domesticates the image: cross-bearing is not a single martyrdom event but an ongoing orientation of life &#8212; a continuous, renewable choice of self-denial over self-preservation.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&#8220;Whoever wants to save their life will lose it, but whoever loses their life for me will save it&#8221; &#8212; the <em>psych&#275;</em> (life/soul) paradox inverts the self-preservation instinct of honor-shame culture. In a social world where protecting one&#8217;s status, family, and life was the primary ethical imperative, the command to surrender life for Jesus&#8217;s sake is radically counter-cultural. The parallel to the Maccabean martyrs (2 Macc 7: seven sons who lost their lives rather than deny Torah) would have provided a framework for comprehension in the early community.</p>",
    "25": "<p>&#8220;What good is it to gain the whole world, yet lose or forfeit their very self?&#8221; &#8212; the rhetorical question assumes that self-loss is a real outcome of world-gain. In Second Temple wealth theology, the rich were often understood to have gained their wealth by trading their relationship with God (cf. Prov 11:4; Sir 31:5&#8211;8; 1 En. 97:8&#8211;10). &#8220;Forfeit their very self&#8221; (<em>heauton apolesas &#275; z&#275;mi&#333;theis</em>) uses commercial vocabulary: a total loss, a write-off of the one asset that cannot be replaced.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&#8220;Whoever is ashamed of me and my words, the Son of Man will be ashamed of them when he comes in his glory&#8221; &#8212; shame (<em>epaischenesthai</em>) in the honor-shame Mediterranean world meant public withdrawal of respect and acknowledgment. In the context of Roman social pressures and Jewish synagogue discipline, public denial of association with Jesus was the primary temptation; the disciple who avoids shame by denying Jesus finds the eschatological judge denying them before the divine court. The threefold glory (Son of Man&#8217;s own, the Father&#8217;s, the holy angels&#8217;) reflects the court scene of Dan 7:13&#8211;14.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&#8220;Some standing here will not taste death before they see the kingdom of God&#8221; &#8212; the Transfiguration (immediately following) is likely the primary referent: three of &#8220;those standing here&#8221; will see the Son of Man in his glory within eight days. The idiom &#8220;taste death&#8221; (<em>geus&#333;ntai thanatou</em>) is a Semitic expression for personally experiencing death (John 8:52; Heb 2:9). The saying&#8217;s open texture allowed multiple fulfillments: Transfiguration, resurrection, Pentecost, and parousia have all been proposed.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&#8220;About eight days after these sayings&#8221; &#8212; Luke&#8217;s interval (Mark/Matthew have &#8220;six days&#8221;) may invoke eighth-day theology: in Jewish thought, the seventh day is Sabbath (completion), the eighth day is eschatological new creation (circumcision on the eighth day, Lev 12:3; the eight-day dedication in 1 Macc 4:56). The Transfiguration on the &#8220;eighth day&#8221; frames it as an eschatological preview. The mountain prayer (unique to Luke) continues his pattern of connecting major revelations with Jesus&#8217;s prayer life.</p>",
    "29": "<p>&#8220;The appearance of his face changed and his clothes became as bright as a flash of lightning&#8221; &#8212; the whiteness (<em>exastrapt&#333;n</em>, flashing like lightning) echoes Daniel&#8217;s heavenly being descriptions (Dan 7:9; 10:6) and anticipates the angels at the resurrection (24:4). Face-radiance recalls Moses after Sinai (Exod 34:29&#8211;35): the divine glory reflected in the face of the one who has been in God&#8217;s presence. Luke&#8217;s light-language is more epiphanic than Mark&#8217;s <em>metamorpho&#333;</em> (transformed) formulation.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Moses and Elijah represent the Law and the Prophets, the two divisions of Hebrew scripture that &#8220;testify&#8221; to Jesus (Luke 24:27,44; John 5:39,46). Their appearance &#8220;in glorious splendour&#8221; (<em>en dox&#275;</em>) &#8212; they share in the divine glory being revealed &#8212; signals that the entire OT revelation participates in this disclosure. Both Moses (death hidden, Deut 34:6) and Elijah (taken up in a whirlwind, 2 Kgs 2:11) had unusual departures, connecting them to the departure topic of their conversation with Jesus (v.31).</p>",
    "31": "<p>&#8220;They spoke about his departure (<em>exodon</em>) which he was about to bring to fulfilment at Jerusalem&#8221; &#8212; Luke&#8217;s unique detail. <em>Exodos</em> is the title of the Exodus book; Luke&#8217;s use is deliberate: Jesus&#8217;s death at Jerusalem is the new Exodus, the ultimate liberation the Egyptian Exodus foreshadowed. The &#8220;fulfilment&#8221; (<em>pl&#275;roun</em>) language frames the Jerusalem passion as the <em>telos</em> toward which the whole narrative moves from this point &#8212; the journey to Jerusalem begun in v.51 is a journey toward the fulfillment of the new-Exodus.</p>",
    "32": "<p>&#8220;Very sleepy&#8221; but &#8220;fully awake&#8221; when they saw his glory &#8212; the disciples&#8217; near-sleep is another Lukan unique detail (paralleled in Gethsemane, 22:45&#8211;46, where they sleep in sorrow). The contrast between drowsy human limitation and the blazing heavenly reality underscores their inability to fully comprehend what they witness. The &#8220;two men standing with him&#8221; &#8212; Moses and Elijah have not yet departed; the disciples wake in time to witness the full theophany before the cloud&#8217;s arrival.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Peter&#8217;s offer to make three <em>sk&#275;nas</em> (shelters/tabernacles) invokes the Feast of Tabernacles (<em>Sukkot</em>), the harvest festival during which Jews dwell in temporary booths recalling the wilderness wandering (Lev 23:42&#8211;43). In some Second Temple traditions, Sukkot was also the festival of the eschatological gathering of nations (Zech 14:16&#8211;19). Peter may be attempting to institutionalize the theophany as a permanent shrine; the cloud-voice that overrides his words signals the moment is for hearing and following, not for permanent structures. Luke adds that Peter &#8220;did not know what he was saying&#8221; &#8212; exonerating him from full blame.</p>",
    "34": "<p>&#8220;A cloud appeared and covered them&#8221; (<em>episkiazein</em>, to overshadow) &#8212; the same verb used for the Holy Spirit&#8217;s overshadowing at the Annunciation (1:35: &#8220;the power of the Most High will overshadow you&#8221;). The Shekinah cloud of Sinai (Exod 19:16&#8211;18; 24:15&#8211;18) and the Tent of Meeting (Exod 40:34&#8211;35) is the type; the cloud is the vehicle of divine presence. &#8220;They were afraid as they entered the cloud&#8221; &#8212; the cloud-entry is theophanic encounter; the fear is the appropriate response to the numinous.</p>",
    "35": "<p>&#8220;This is my Son, whom I have chosen; listen to him&#8221; &#8212; combining Ps 2:7 (&#8220;my Son&#8221;, the royal-messianic oracle), Isa 42:1 (&#8220;my chosen one,&#8221; the Servant poem), and Deut 18:15 (&#8220;listen to him,&#8221; the prophet-like-Moses promise). Luke&#8217;s &#8220;whom I have chosen&#8221; (<em>ho eklelegmenos</em>) is more explicitly Servant-language than Mark/Matthew&#8217;s &#8220;in whom I am well pleased.&#8221; The Deut 18:15 &#8220;listen to him&#8221; command makes the Transfiguration the divine authentication of Jesus as the authoritative teacher &#8212; the <em>bat qol</em> (divine voice) endorses his words as Torah.</p>",
    "36": "<p>&#8220;The disciples kept this to themselves and told no one at that time&#8221; &#8212; the Lukan silence command (Mark 9:9 adds the temporal qualifier &#8220;until the Son of Man has risen from the dead&#8221;). The disciples&#8217; silence is appropriate: the Transfiguration&#8217;s meaning is only fully comprehensible in resurrection light. The early community&#8217;s use of the Transfiguration narrative to confirm resurrection-reality is preserved in 2 Pet 1:16&#8211;18, which cites it explicitly as eyewitness evidence: &#8220;we were eyewitnesses of his majesty.&#8221;</p>",
    "37": "<p>The abrupt transition from mountain-glory to valley-need (&#8220;the next day, when they came down from the mountain, a large crowd met him&#8221;) patterns revelation on the mountain against engagement in the valley. The structural parallel to Moses at Sinai (Exod 32: Moses descends to find the golden-calf apostasy) and Elijah at Horeb (1 Kgs 19: divine voice, then immediate re-commission) positions the Transfiguration-to-healing sequence as a typological descent into human affliction after divine encounter.</p>",
    "38": "<p>&#8220;My only child&#8221; (<em>monogen&#275;s</em>) &#8212; Luke&#8217;s consistent emphasis on the irreplaceable uniqueness of the person in need: the Nain widow&#8217;s only son (7:12), Jairus&#8217;s only daughter (8:42), and this boy. The pattern accumulates to a theological claim: Jesus restores what cannot be replaced, anticipating the resurrection. The father&#8217;s cry (<em>epiblepsai epi ton huion mou</em>, look upon my son) echoes the prayer of Hannah (1 Sam 1:11) and the Psalms of the afflicted who appeal to divine mercy.</p>",
    "39": "<p>The symptom description (seizing, screaming, convulsing, foaming, barely leaving him) matches a severe seizure disorder; Luke the physician&#8217;s vocabulary is notably precise. In Second Temple Jewish cosmology, epilepsy and convulsive disorders were attributed to demonic causation (cf. the Qumran <em>Prayer of Nabonidus</em>, 4Q242, where an affliction is attributed to demonic influence and healed by a Jewish exorcist). The exorcism is simultaneously a medical healing and a spiritual deliverance.</p>",
    "40": "<p>The disciples&#8217; failure to exorcise drives the narrative. Mark 9:28&#8211;29 records Jesus&#8217;s private explanation: &#8220;this kind comes out only by prayer&#8221; (some manuscripts add &#8220;and fasting&#8221;). The failure of the nine disciples (Peter, James, and John were on the mountain) represents the limits of delegated authority exercised without sufficient prayer-dependence on the source. The structural irony: Jesus has just descended from mountain prayer (vv.28&#8211;36) to find that prayer-based exorcism has failed in his absence.</p>",
    "41": "<p>&#8220;Faithless and perverse generation&#8221; (<em>genea apistos kai diestrammen&#275;</em>) &#8212; a near-quotation of Deut 32:5,20 LXX (&#8220;a crooked and twisted generation,&#8221; &#8220;a faithless generation&#8221;). Moses used this language at the Song of Moses about Israel&#8217;s apostasy at the end of the wilderness period. Jesus&#8217;s application to his own disciples and the crowd frames their failure as analogous to Israel&#8217;s wilderness faithlessness &#8212; the generation that could not enter the Promised Land because of unbelief (Num 14:11; Ps 95:10&#8211;11; Heb 3:10&#8211;11).</p>",
    "42": "<p>&#8220;The demon threw him to the ground in a convulsion&#8221; &#8212; the spirit&#8217;s violent final act before expulsion is a common exorcism-narrative pattern (Mark 1:26; 9:26). Jesus&#8217;s rebuking of the unclean spirit (<em>epetim&#275;sen t&#333; pneumati t&#333; akatharto</em>) and the healing, followed by restoration to the father, repeats the Elijah-Elisha pattern (1 Kgs 17:23: Elijah gave him to his mother; 2 Kgs 4:36&#8211;37: Elisha gave the child to his mother) &#8212; Jesus exceeds both prophets by speaking a single command without physical manipulation.</p>",
    "43": "<p>&#8220;They were all amazed at the greatness of God&#8221; (<em>emegaly non ton theon</em>, they magnified God) &#8212; the same verb as the Magnificat (1:46: &#8220;my soul magnifies the Lord&#8221;). The crowd&#8217;s theocentric response is the correct pattern Luke models: the beneficiary of healing glorifies God, not the healer (5:25&#8211;26; 7:16; 13:13; 17:15; 18:43). While they are still marveling &#8212; at the peak of their amazement &#8212; Jesus issues the second passion prediction: the juxtaposition frames the coming suffering against the backdrop of popular acclaim.</p>",
    "44": "<p>&#8220;Put these words into your ears&#8221; (<em>esthesthe hymeis eis ta &#333;ta hym&#333;n tous logous toutous</em>) &#8212; the Hebraism &#8220;put into the ears&#8221; (<em>sim be&#8217;oznayim</em>, Exod 17:14; Num 14:28; Judg 9:2) requires careful retention of a critical announcement. The second passion prediction (&#8220;the Son of Man is going to be delivered into the hands of men&#8221;) is more compressed than the first (v.22) and uses &#8220;delivered&#8221; (<em>paradidosthai</em>), the same word used for Judas&#8217;s betrayal (22:4,21,22) &#8212; linking the divine necessity to human treachery.</p>",
    "45": "<p>&#8220;It was hidden from them&#8221; (<em>parakekalymmenon ap aut&#333;n</em>) &#8212; a divine passive: God conceals the passion meaning from the disciples until the post-resurrection opening of scripture (24:45&#8211;46: &#8220;then he opened their minds so they could understand the scriptures&#8221;). The disciples&#8217; non-understanding is not stupidity but providential withholding; the time for understanding is not yet. Their fear of asking him reflects the honor-shame dynamic: admitting non-understanding might expose inadequacy to the teacher.</p>",
    "46": "<p>The argument about greatness (<em>dialogismos</em>, internal reasoning/dispute) arises in the context of the Jerusalem journey announcement and the two passion predictions. In Second Temple messianic expectation, the Davidic kingdom would involve the exaltation of the righteous to positions of honor and administrative authority (cf. Dan 7:27; 1 En. 108:12). The disciples&#8217; argument reflects serious theological expectations about how the kingdom would operate &#8212; by honor-hierarchies, but with the &#8220;right&#8221; people elevated.</p>",
    "47": "<p>&#8220;Jesus, knowing their thoughts&#8221; (<em>id&#333;n ton dialogismon t&#275;s kardias aut&#333;n</em>) &#8212; prophetic knowledge of interior states, attributed to God in 1 Kgs 8:39 (&#8220;you alone know the hearts of all people&#8221;) and Ps 44:21, is applied to Jesus here and at 5:22. The child placed beside him is a deliberate visual argument: children in antiquity were legal minors, social non-persons, low in all honor ratings. To welcome a child is to welcome one who has no reciprocal honor to give &#8212; pure, non-reciprocal service, the antithesis of status-seeking.</p>",
    "48": "<p>&#8220;Whoever welcomes this little child in my name welcomes me; and whoever welcomes me welcomes the one who sent me&#8221; &#8212; the <em>sheliach</em> chain of authorization (child &#8594; Jesus &#8594; Father) inverts the honor hierarchy by making the lowest link (the child) the entry point for the highest. &#8220;Whoever is least among you all is the greatest&#8221; reverses the honor-shame metric: willingness to serve the socially negligible is the greatness indicator. The three-level chain also functions as a Christological claim: receiving Jesus = receiving the Father.</p>",
    "49": "<p>The unknown exorcist is driving out demons &#8220;in your name&#8221; without being part of the formal disciple group. John&#8217;s complaint (&#8220;he is not one of us&#8221;) applies the exclusive community-boundary logic that defines insiders by formal association. In Second Temple Judaism, the use of powerful names in exorcism was broadly practiced (cf. Acts 19:13&#8211;16, Jewish exorcists invoking &#8220;the Jesus whom Paul preaches&#8221;); the question is whether effective use of the name indicates genuine authorization or unauthorized appropriation.</p>",
    "50": "<p>&#8220;Whoever is not against you is for you&#8221; &#8212; the inclusive formulation that broadens the circle of those allied with the mission. Luke 11:23 has the opposite saying (&#8220;whoever is not with me is against me&#8221;) in the Beelzebul controversy, where spiritual allegiance is binary. The two sayings are not contradictory: the first (9:50) addresses those who effectively use Jesus&#8217;s name without formal membership; the second (11:23) addresses those who attribute Jesus&#8217;s work to Satan &#8212; two distinct situations requiring opposite responses.</p>",
    "51": "<p>&#8220;Jesus resolutely set out for Jerusalem&#8221; (<em>est&#275;risen to pros&#333;pon autou tou poreuesthai eis Ierousal&#275;m</em>) &#8212; the Hebraism &#8220;set the face toward&#8221; (<em>sim panim&#8217;el</em>) denotes determined, purposeful direction (cf. Isa 50:7: &#8220;I set my face like a flint&#8221;). The Lukan travel narrative begins here and extends to 19:44 (approximately 43% of the Gospel); the Jerusalem journey is the structural and theological center of Luke-Acts. &#8220;The time approaching for him to be taken up&#8221; frames the journey as moving toward both the passion and the Ascension.</p>",
    "52": "<p>The sending of messengers ahead (<em>aposteilas angelous pro pros&#333;pou autou</em>) echoes Mal 3:1 (&#8220;I will send my messenger ahead of you, who will prepare the way&#8221;) &#8212; the same text applied to John the Baptist in 7:27. The Samaritan village lay on the direct route from Galilee through Samaria to Jerusalem, the shorter path that many Jews avoided. The messengers&#8217; advance mission is practical hospitality preparation, but their Jerusalem-destination disclosure (v.53) triggers the refusal.</p>",
    "53": "<p>&#8220;The people there did not welcome him, because he was heading for Jerusalem&#8221; &#8212; the refusal is explicitly theological and geographic: Gerizim vs. Jerusalem was the defining Jewish-Samaritan conflict (John 4:20&#8211;21). Josephus records violent incidents between Samaritans and Galilean pilgrims in the first century (<em>Ant.</em> 20.118&#8211;136). The refusal is not random xenophobia but structured by the Jerusalem-pilgrimage context &#8212; refusing to host those honoring a rival worship site. The irony is that a Samaritan will be the hero of 10:33.</p>",
    "54": "<p>James and John&#8217;s fire-from-heaven request invokes the Elijah precedent: 2 Kgs 1:9&#8211;14 records Elijah calling down fire on two sets of fifty soldiers sent by King Ahaziah. The disciples propose to function as Elijah-like prophets exercising judgment against those who refuse the prophet&#8217;s message. The precedent is canonically valid but theologically misapplied: Elijah&#8217;s fire-judgment was against apostasy and idolatry, not hospitality refusal. Jesus&#8217;s refusal defines the kingdom mission&#8217;s character as distinctly non-judgment in this mode.</p>",
    "55": "<p>&#8220;Jesus turned and rebuked them&#8221; &#8212; the rebuke (<em>epetim&#275;sen</em>) is the same word used for rebuking demons and illness (4:35,39; 8:24; 9:42). Some manuscripts add: &#8220;You do not know what kind of spirit you are of, for the Son of Man did not come to destroy people&#8217;s lives but to save them&#8221; &#8212; a textual variant that makes the anti-judgment principle explicit. The disciples&#8217; desire for fire-from-heaven reveals a fundamental misunderstanding of the mission&#8217;s character that the Good Samaritan parable (10:25&#8211;37) will address directly.</p>",
    "56": "<p>&#8220;They went to another village&#8221; &#8212; the undramatic resolution: no judgment, no confrontation, simply a quiet departure. This is precisely the instruction of vv.3&#8211;5: when unwelcome, move on. The episode functions as a character study: the disciples&#8217; instinct is to use power for revenge; Jesus&#8217;s instinct is to seek another opening. The contrast between the disciples&#8217; fire-request and the Good Samaritan&#8217;s compassion (a Samaritan helping a Jew on this same road) will be the ironic reversal Luke sets up.</p>",
    "57": "<p>The three would-be follower dialogues (vv.57&#8211;62) cluster at the opening of the travel narrative, setting the tone for the discipleship journey to Jerusalem. The first man offers total commitment without conditions: &#8220;I will follow you wherever you go.&#8221; In the honor-shame context, attaching oneself to a successful teacher-prophet enhanced one&#8217;s social standing; the crowd following Jesus at this point is considerable. Jesus&#8217;s response does not encourage the offer but honestly discloses its cost &#8212; testing whether the man&#8217;s commitment is based on calculation or on genuine call.</p>",
    "58": "<p>&#8220;Foxes have dens and birds have nests, but the Son of Man has nowhere to lay his head&#8221; &#8212; the contrast between the natural provision for wild creatures and the deliberate homelessness of the one who has relinquished normal social structures. In the Galilean context, foxes and birds were common in the agricultural landscape. The <em>Son of Man</em> title used for the itinerant, homeless teacher may also be read generically (&#8220;bar nasha&#8221; = a human being): &#8220;even animals have homes; a person like me has none.&#8221; The itinerant lifestyle was sustained entirely by hospitality networks.</p>",
    "59": "<p>&#8220;First let me go and bury my father&#8221; &#8212; burying one&#8217;s father was among the most sacred obligations in Jewish law. Tobit 4:3 and 14:10 make it a religious duty; b. Ber 17b&#8211;18a rules that one is exempt from all other commandments while performing burial obligations; Josephus (<em>Ag. Ap.</em> 2.205) lists burial among the fundamental laws of Jewish piety. The man&#8217;s request invokes the most unassailable religious duty. The father may not yet be dead (&#8220;first let me wait until he dies, then I&#8217;ll follow&#8221;) or may have just died.</p>",
    "60": "<p>&#8220;Let the dead bury their own dead&#8221; (<em>aphes tous nekrous thapsai tous heaut&#333;n nekrous</em>) &#8212; one of the most radical sayings in the Synoptics. The first &#8220;dead&#8221; are the spiritually dead (outside the kingdom); the second &#8220;dead&#8221; are the literally dead who need burial. The kingdom call creates a primary obligation that overrides even the most sacred family duty. The Elisha parallel (1 Kgs 19:19&#8211;21): Elisha asked to kiss his parents goodbye; Elijah permitted it. Jesus&#8217;s standard is more absolute than Elijah&#8217;s &#8212; the urgency of the kingdom proclamation admits no delay.</p>",
    "61": "<p>&#8220;I will follow you, Lord; but first let me go back and say goodbye to my family&#8221; &#8212; the request echoes Elisha&#8217;s exactly (1 Kgs 19:20: &#8220;Let me kiss my father and mother goodbye, and then I will follow you&#8221;). Elijah permitted it; Jesus uses the request as the occasion for the plow-saying of v.62. The farewell-to-family request also evokes Ruth&#8217;s choice: Orpah said farewell and returned home; Ruth refused. The third enquirer faces the Orpah-Ruth choice &#8212; the decisive break with the old life that genuine vocation requires.</p>",
    "62": "<p>&#8220;No one who puts a hand to the plow and looks back is fit for service in the kingdom of God&#8221; &#8212; plowing requires looking forward: the furrow must be kept straight, which requires fixing one&#8217;s gaze on a point at the far end of the field. Looking backward creates a curved furrow wasting the field. The agricultural image combines with the Elisha precedent: Elisha was plowing when called (1 Kgs 19:19); he slaughtered his oxen and burned his plow &#8212; a no-turning-back gesture that Jesus&#8217;s saying demands. The kingdom requires the same irreversible commitment that Israel&#8217;s prophetic callings required.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'luke')
    merge_comm(existing, DATA)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH9)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'luke', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f"Luke mkt-context: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses written.")

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
